Comprehensive QA Audit Report

System: EU→CIS Concierge Delivery Platform
Backend: Django 6 / DRF / SQLite3 (delivery-service)
Mobile: Flutter / Riverpod / GoRouter (mobile-ds)
Audit date: 2026-06-21

---
Critical

---
C-1 — Hardcoded localhost base URL in mobile app — production connection failure

Severity: Critical
File: mobile-ds/lib/core/network/api_endpoints.dart:3

Description:
The mobile API base URL is http://localhost:8000/api/v1. On any real Android or iOS device, localhost resolves to the device itself, not the server. Every API call fails immediately. The URL also uses plain HTTP instead of HTTPS.

Steps to reproduce:
1. Install the app on a physical device.
2. Attempt login.

Expected: Login succeeds against the backend server.
Actual: Network error — cannot connect to localhost:8000.

Root cause: Development placeholder was never parameterised.

Recommended fix:
Drive the base URL from environment/flavor configuration (--dart-define=API_BASE_URL=https://api.example.com); remove the hard-coded default. Enforce HTTPS.

---
C-2 — Zombie authenticated state after refresh-token expiry

Severity: Critical
File: mobile-ds/lib/core/network/auth_interceptor.dart:62-65

Description:
When the JWT refresh call fails (expired refresh token, revoked token), the interceptor clears stored tokens but never notifies AuthNotifier. The routerProvider redirect only fires when authNotifierProvider emits a new state. The app remains on authenticated routes, all subsequent API calls return 401, and the user cannot log in again without force-killing the app.

Steps to reproduce:
1. Log in; let the refresh token expire server-side or manually revoke it.
2. Open any screen that calls the API.

Expected: App redirects to /login.
Actual: Error banners appear on every screen; the app never navigates to /login.

Root cause:
} on DioException {
    await tokenStorage.clearTokens();
    return handler.next(err);  // auth state is never updated
}

Recommended fix:
Inject a reference to AuthNotifier (or use a global Ref) into AuthInterceptor and call ref.read(authNotifierProvider.notifier).logout() (or equivalent state update) when refresh fails.

---
C-3 — Default DEBUG=True and insecure SECRET_KEY in production

Severity: Critical
Files: config/settings.py:37-48

Description:
If deployed without setting DJANGO_DEBUG=false and DJANGO_SECRET_KEY, the server runs with DEBUG=True (full tracebacks returned to clients) and the publicly committed insecure secret key. This exposes stack traces, internal paths, database structure, and invalidates all session/CSRF security.

Steps to reproduce:
Deploy without setting the environment variables and trigger a server error.

Expected: Opaque 500 response.
Actual: Full Django debug traceback including code, local variables, and SQL queries returned to the client.

Root cause:
SECRET_KEY = os.environ.get("DJANGO_SECRET_KEY", "django-insecure-…")
DEBUG = os.environ.get("DJANGO_DEBUG", "true").lower() == "true"

Recommended fix:
When DEBUG=False, raise ImproperlyConfigured if DJANGO_SECRET_KEY is not set. Set the env-var default for DJANGO_DEBUG to "false".

