High

---
H-1 — Registration race condition causes unhandled 500 on duplicate email

Severity: High
File: delivery/api/v1/auth/serializers.py:32-35

Description:
validate_email checks for existing emails with filter(email__iexact=value), then returns the value. Between the check and the create_user() call, a concurrent identical request can pass the same check. create_user() then raises django.db.IntegrityError (unique constraint), which is not caught by the DRF serializer layer or the custom exception handler and surfaces as a 500 Internal Server Error.

Steps to reproduce:
Send two simultaneous POST /auth/register requests with the same email.

Expected: Second request returns 400 with "Email already exists."
Actual: One request returns 500.

Root cause: TOCTOU (time-of-check-time-of-use) race; IntegrityError not caught.

Recommended fix:
Wrap User.objects.create_user(...) in try/except IntegrityError and convert it to a serializers.ValidationError.

---
H-2 — LocMemCache incompatible with multi-process Gunicorn

Severity: High
File: config/settings.py:454-459

Description:
LocMemCache is process-local. With Gunicorn running multiple workers, each worker maintains its own isolated in-memory cache. Currency rate invalidation (CurrencyRateService.invalidate()), footer cache invalidation, and DeliverySetting.get_settings() are all backed by this cache. A rate update processed in worker A is invisible to workers B, C, D until their cache expires naturally. Customers can see stale FX rates mid-session.

Steps to reproduce:
Run Gunicorn with --workers 4, update a currency rate, and observe that some API requests still return the old rate.

Expected: All workers reflect the new rate within one cache TTL.
Actual: Rate is stale in 3 out of 4 workers indefinitely.

Root cause: Per-process in-memory cache does not share state across OS processes.

Recommended fix:
Replace LocMemCache with FileBasedCache (viable for single-server without Redis) or add Redis when scaling. Alternatively, remove caching on objects that are rarely updated and always hit the DB.

---
H-3 — N+1 query on order list (item_count)

Severity: High
File: delivery/api/v1/orders/serializers.py:41-42

Description:
OrderListSerializer.get_item_count calls obj.items.count(), executing one SQL COUNT query per order in the paginated list. With a page size of 20 orders, the list endpoint fires 21 SQL queries (1 for orders + 20 for counts).

Steps to reproduce:
Call GET /api/v1/orders with Django's DEBUG_QUERIES enabled on a user with 20 orders.

Expected: 1–2 queries (orders + prefetch).
Actual: 21 queries; response time scales linearly with page size.

Root cause: Lazy evaluation of reverse relation inside serializer without prefetch.

Recommended fix:
In the selector (get_user_orders), use queryset.annotate(item_count=Count('items')) and add item_count as a read-only integer field in OrderListSerializer (removing the SerializerMethodField).

---
H-4 — No rate limiting on authentication endpoints

Severity: High
File: config/settings.py (REST_FRAMEWORK section) — missing throttle config

Description:
POST /auth/login and POST /auth/register have no throttling. An attacker can attempt unlimited password guesses against any email address without restrictions.

Steps to reproduce:
Send 1,000 login requests in a loop for a known email.

Expected: Requests throttled after N attempts (HTTP 429).
Actual: All requests processed; password brute force is unrestricted.

Root cause: DEFAULT_THROTTLE_CLASSES is not configured in REST_FRAMEWORK.

Recommended fix:
Add DRF's AnonRateThrottle / UserRateThrottle to DEFAULT_THROTTLE_CLASSES, or use a reverse-proxy-level rate limit (nginx limit_req). Apply a strict per-IP limit (e.g., 10/min) on auth endpoints specifically.

---
H-5 — validate_items unconditionally requires ≥1 item, blocks API SEND orders

Severity: High
File: delivery/api/v1/orders/serializers.py:82-85

Description:
OrderCreateSerializer.validate_items raises ValidationError("At least one item is required.") if the items list is empty. The field default is default=list, so if items is omitted entirely, it defaults to [] and triggers the validator. SEND orders (order_type=SEND) don't require items at creation time — items are added later by admin. Any API client (or automated test) that submits a SEND order without items gets a 422 error.

Steps to reproduce:
POST /api/v1/orders
{"order_type": "SEND", "destination_country": "RU"}

Expected: 201 Created — SEND order created with no items.
Actual: 422 Validation error — "At least one item is required."

Root cause: Validator doesn't check order_type before applying the item constraint.

Recommended fix:
Move the "at least one item" check inside the serializer's top-level validate() method and gate it on order_type == 'BUY'.

