Medium

---
M-1 — Service-tracking fields omitted from OrderDetailSerializer

Severity: Medium
File: delivery/api/v1/orders/serializers.py:58-69

Description:
For SEND orders with transfer_method=SERVICE, the fields service_tracking, service_carrier, service_store, and service_pickup_code are stored on the order but not included in OrderDetailSerializer.Meta.fields. Mobile users with SERVICE orders can't see their tracking number or carrier through the API.

Recommended fix:
Add the four service_* fields to OrderDetailSerializer and update the Flutter OrderDetail model accordingly.

---
M-2 — Promo code and financial breakdown fields absent from API

Severity: Medium
File: delivery/api/v1/orders/serializers.py

Description:
promo_code_id, promo_discount_czk, promo_applied, delivery_cost_czk, and locked_czk_rate are not returned by OrderDetailSerializer. Clients cannot display the applied discount or understand the full pricing breakdown (especially for legacy CZK delivery cost orders).

Recommended fix:
Add read-only representations of promo and legacy CZK fields to the serializer.

---
M-3 — localCacheProvider timing issue silently skips profile caching

Severity: Medium
File: mobile-ds/lib/features/auth/providers/auth_provider.dart:99-104

Description:
_cacheProfile reads ref.read(localCacheProvider).valueOrNull. localCacheProvider is a FutureProvider; if SharedPreferences.getInstance() hasn't completed yet (first startup), valueOrNull is null and the profile is silently not persisted. On the next cold start with no network, the offline fallback returns null and the user is logged out despite having valid credentials.

Recommended fix:
Await localCacheProvider in AuthNotifier.build() before attempting to cache — the provider is already awaited there implicitly. For _cacheProfile, use await ref.read(localCacheProvider.future) instead of .valueOrNull.

---
M-4 — delivery_type deprecated field still in active validation code path

Severity: Medium
Files: delivery/models.py:229-238, delivery/services/validation.py:39, delivery/models.py:410-418

Description:
Order.delivery_type is marked "устарел" (deprecated) in verbose name but is still checked in OrderValidationService.validate_for_payment_approval and in Order.save() (legacy branch). This creates two parallel code paths for delivery method validation that can give inconsistent results. A VERIFICATION→AWAITING_PAYMENT transition can succeed if delivery_type is set even when delivery_method_ref is the intended field.

Recommended fix:
Create a data migration to set delivery_method_ref for all orders that still have only delivery_type set; then remove the legacy branch from Order.save() and the validation service.

---
M-5 — Auth retry uses bare _refreshClient, bypasses main-client interceptors

Severity: Medium
File: mobile-ds/lib/core/network/auth_interceptor.dart:60

Description:
After a successful token refresh, the original request is retried with _refreshClient.fetch(err.requestOptions). _refreshClient is a bare Dio instance without any logging, error-normalisation, or other interceptors attached to the main apiClientProvider. Retry responses skip whatever middleware the main client applies.

Recommended fix:
Store a reference to the main Dio instance in AuthInterceptor and use it for the retry: final retryResponse = await _mainClient.fetch(err.requestOptions).

---
M-6 — Testimonial.rating has no 1–5 range enforcement

Severity: Medium
File: delivery/models.py:1836

Description:
rating = models.PositiveSmallIntegerField(default=5)
No validators=[MinValueValidator(1), MaxValueValidator(5)]. Admin can save ratings of 0 or 100, which would render oddly on the landing page star widget.

Recommended fix:
Add validators=[MinValueValidator(1), MaxValueValidator(5)] and a migration.

---
M-7 — cancel_order exposed via DELETE verb returns a body

Severity: Medium
File: delivery/api/v1/orders/views.py:109-120

Description:
REST convention: DELETE deletes a resource and returns 204 No Content. This endpoint cancels the order (a state transition) and returns the updated order body with HTTP 200. This breaks OpenAPI client code generators and is misleading in logs and monitoring.

Recommended fix:
Add a cancel action (POST /orders/{id}/cancel) and deprecate the DELETE path, or at minimum document the deviation clearly in the OpenAPI spec.

---
Low

---
L-1 — ALLOWED_HOSTS footgun when DEBUG=False without env var

Severity: Low
File: config/settings.py:46-50

Description:
When DEBUG=False and DJANGO_ALLOWED_HOSTS is not set, ALLOWED_HOSTS evaluates to []. Django blocks all requests with "Bad Request (400)". A deployment that forgets the env var silently goes down.

Recommended fix:
Add a startup check: if DEBUG=False and not ALLOWED_HOSTS, raise ImproperlyConfigured.

---
L-2 — ProviderContainer in main.dart never disposed

Severity: Low
File: mobile-ds/lib/main.dart:11

Description:
The manually created ProviderContainer is never disposed when the app exits. On platforms where the Dart VM doesn't terminate cleanly (background service scenarios), this leaks all provider subscriptions.

Recommended fix:
Wrap UncontrolledProviderScope teardown to call container.dispose(), or prefer ProviderScope (which handles disposal) and move the FCM setup into a provider initialized after the scope.

---
L-3 — No CAPTCHA or rate limit on shipping calculator form

Severity: Low
File: delivery/models.py:1711-1751 (ShippingCalculatorRequest)

Description:
The lead-capture shipping calculator form stores visitor email addresses and product URLs. There is no CAPTCHA, honeypot, or server-side rate limit. The form can be used to harvest valid emails, spam the admin inbox, or GDPR-scrape contact data.

Recommended fix:
Add IP-based rate limiting at the view level and a simple honeypot field on the form.

---
L-4 — FCM callback has no error handling

Severity: Low
File: mobile-ds/lib/main.dart:19-21

Description:
The FCM message callback calls container.read(notificationsNotifierProvider.notifier).add(...) without try/catch. If notificationsNotifierProvider is in an error state (storage failure), this throws an uncaught exception in a global callback context, which Flutter reports as an unhandled platform exception.

Recommended fix:
Wrap the callback body in try/catch (_) with a debugPrint fallback.

---
L-5 — Redundant absolute URL construction in AuthInterceptor

Severity: Low
File: mobile-ds/lib/core/network/auth_interceptor.dart:47-50

Description:
final response = await _refreshClient.post(
  '${ApiEndpoints.baseUrl}${ApiEndpoints.refresh}',  // full URL
  ...
);
_refreshClient already has baseUrl: ApiEndpoints.baseUrl. Passing the full absolute URL is redundant (Dio detects the http:// prefix and ignores baseUrl). This is not a bug but creates confusion.

Recommended fix:
Use just ApiEndpoints.refresh as the path.

---
L-6 — Order state machine doesn't differentiate SEND vs BUY pipeline

Severity: Low
File: delivery/api/v1/core/state_machines.py

Description:
OrderStateMachine.TRANSITIONS applies identically to both BUY and SEND orders. SEND orders that go through PURCHASED/EU_WAREHOUSE stages might not semantically apply (the service is sending the customer's own items, not purchasing them). If business rules diverge between types, the unified machine is a maintenance hazard.

Recommended fix:
Document in code (or via a type-specific validator) which transitions are valid for which order type. If the pipelines truly unify, add a comment to that effect.

